To create an intent in Android using Java, follow these steps:

Step 1: Create a new Intent object
```java
Intent intent = new Intent(context, YourActivity.class);
```
Replace `YourActivity` with the class you want to open.

Step 2: Add extra data (optional)
If you need to pass any data to the activity, you can use the `putExtra()` method:
```java
intent.putExtra("key", value);
```
Replace `"key"` with a unique identifier and `value` with the actual data.

Step 3: Start the activity
You can start the activity using `startActivity()` method:
```java
startActivity(intent);
```
Make sure your context is the appropriate `Activity` or `Context` object.

Example: Creating an intent to open a new activity and passing data

```java
Intent intent = new Intent(MainActivity.this, SecondActivity.class);
intent.putExtra("name", "John");
intent.putExtra("age", 25);
startActivity(intent);
```

In the `SecondActivity`, you can retrieve the data using the following code:
```java
Intent intent = getIntent();
String name = intent.getStringExtra("name");
int age = intent.getIntExtra("age", -1);
```

Note: Replace `MainActivity` and `SecondActivity` with your actual activity names.

To set an activity to go back to its parent in Android, you can use the `NavUtils` class along with the `getParentActivityIntent()` method. Here's how to do it in Java:

Step 1: Import the necessary classes
```java
import android.support.v4.app.NavUtils;
```

Step 2: Set the parent activity in the manifest
In the AndroidManifest.xml file, ensure that the parent activity is defined for the activity you want to go back from. Add the `android:parentActivityName` attribute to the activity tag:
```xml
<activity
    android:name=".ChildActivity"
    android:parentActivityName=".ParentActivity" >
</activity>
```
Replace `.ChildActivity` with the actual child activity class name and `.ParentActivity` with the actual parent activity class name.

Step 3: Handle the Up button or onBackPressed() method in the child activity
Override the `onOptionsItemSelected()` method and handle the home button click. Call the `NavUtils` class to navigate up to the parent activity:
```java
@Override
public boolean onOptionsItemSelected(MenuItem item) {
    switch (item.getItemId()) {
        case android.R.id.home:
            NavUtils.navigateUpFromSameTask(this);
            return true;
    }
    return super.onOptionsItemSelected(item);
}
```
Alternatively, you can handle the back button press in the `onBackPressed()` method:
```java
@Override
public void onBackPressed() {
    NavUtils.navigateUpFromSameTask(this);
}
```

That's it! Now when the user clicks the Up button or the back button, the activity will navigate back to its parent activity.
